Parameters and Arguments:
        - terms used to refer to values that are passed into a method
        -> public static void displayValue (int num)<-parameter, if parameter there NEED to have argument
            {sout("the value is " + num);}
            public static void main (String[] args){
            displayValue(5);} /*<-5 is argument*/

        What to know on Parameters:
        - parameters are variables declared in the method
        - must have name and data type
        - parameter  act as placeholder for argument when method is being called
        -  methods can have 0 + parameters
        What to know on Arguments:
        - they are actual values passed into a method when invoking (calling) a method
        - need to be in parenthesis
        - can be values or variables (variables have values in them too)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
pass-by value: - copy of the value of an argument is passed to a method, even when dealing with objects
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Argument and Parameter Data type Compatibility:
 - rules are same with assigning values to variables (e.g. can assignm byte to int , or int to byte)
 - data type must match or be compatible for assignment to be valid(if parameter int you can pass int, byte, short
                                                                    as argument but not double or float)
  -> can pass narrower data type to wider one with implicit casting (short fits into int so implicit)
  -> can pass wider data type to narrower one with explicit casting
        (-> long cannot fit into int so it's not compatible
         so I need to explicitly name it before variable,
         e.g. long num3 =15; display(int)num3); =>explicit casting
==> methods can have 0 + parameters
==> num and order of arguments must match
